wrecked.definition: To destroy violently; to cause severe damage to something, to a point where it no longer works, or is useless.

mooch.example1: Besides the fact that he was a dirty, lying mooch, of course.

bluffing.definition: To make a bluff; to give the impression that one's hand is stronger than it is.

liftoff.definition: The point in the launch of a rocket or an aircraft where it leaves contact with the ground.
liftoff.example1: There's just no way that could have happened before liftoff.

restoring.definition: To reestablish, or bring back into existence.
restoring.example1: Aurelia glanced unseeingly at the huge shambling animal, but she didn’t wait to see it go through its weary tricks, restoring the old carefree spirit to the great audience.
restoring.example2: But immigration is merely restoring the diversity that America held for thousands of years.
restoring.example3: It was merely a few words of encouragement, the sort of words that are uttered in the din of battle, not distinguishable individually but restoring confidence by the fact of being spoken.

odorless.example1: Neither do the ads for an electronic device that dispenses lindane fumes — we are told that it is safe and odorless.

magnate.example1: More than that, surely; a chocolate magnate, the creator of Amo.

ministerial.definition: A member of the mediaeval estate or caste of unfree nobles.

ministerial.example2: Within a year, Oliver and I discovered that under the Urban Areas Act we were not permitted to occupy business premises in the city without ministerial consent.

lister.definition: A spear armed with three or more prongs, for striking fish.
lister.example1: He pronounced the words lazily, blunting the t’s to d’s so that it sounded like “siddle lister.”
lister.example2: Globules of perspiration glistened like transparent pearls around his mustache and swelled like opaque listers under his eyes.

swami.definition: (used as a title) A Hindu ascetic or religious teacher.
swami.example1: It was far less, though, than the $50 million debut that many box office swamis had predicted.

biofuel.definition: Any fuel that is obtained from a renewable biological resource, especially from biomass
biofuel.example1: The resulting algae could then be employed to create biofuels.
biofuel.example2: Buoyed by a rise in oil prices and Norway’s generous welfare state, Oslo has invested heavily in sustainability initiatives: hydropower plants, biofuel buses, electric cars, an energy-positive airport city.
biofuel.example3: Just don't expect the flight to be totally carbon-neutral--regulators limit the use of biofuels to a 50-50 blend with conventional jet fuel.

vilify.definition: To say defamatory things about someone or something; to speak ill of.
vilify.example1: Thus, the Party rejects and vilifies every principle for which the Socialist movement originally stood, and it chooses to do this in the name of Socialism.

rehydrate.definition: To resupply with water that has been removed or lost; to moisten something that has dried.

deltoid.definition: The deltoid muscle, a triangular muscle on the human shoulder.
deltoid.example1: They would aim for the muscle that Tariq, in a professorial voice, called the deltoid.
deltoid.example2: He wears a Pagoda shirt that’s a tiny bit small for him, so his biceps and deltoids are really defined and I can’t help but want to squeeze them.

reshoot.example1: “I hate reshooting, but you have to be able to look at stuff and say it doesn’t work,” Mr. Wolf said.

underwhelming.definition: Failing to interest; not as exciting as promised or expected.
underwhelming.example1: She doesn’t understand why these Deckers aren’t home with loved ones, particularly those two teen boys today, who, as they were leaving, talked about how underwhelming the virtual reality experience was.
underwhelming.example2: So far, our discoveries had been underwhelming, which was how I liked them.
underwhelming.example3: Does she really want to hear about her daughter’s deeply underwhelming and unhappy existence in school?

dyslexia.definition: A learning disability characterized by reading and writing difficulties.
dyslexia.example1: As a matter of fact, when I told one teacher in jr. high that I thought I had dyslexia, he told me that I was just lazy.
dyslexia.example2: From there we can crank the microscope one more turn to the level of genes, which is an opportunity to review studies of dyslexia and other inherited language disorders.
dyslexia.example3: “You don’t have dyslexia,” she said at last.

testicular.definition: Pertaining to one or more testicles; of the testicle(s).
testicular.example1: He suspected that the tissue mass he had palpated inside me was testicular.
testicular.example2: “A bootlicker too. You lack the requisite spine and testicular fortitude to study under me.”
testicular.example3: One of the worst cases of this testicular infection appeared in a morgue attendant who had handled Marburg-infected bodies and who himself came down with Marburg, having caught it from the cadavers.

reshaping.definition: To make into a different shape
reshaping.example1: The great change in attitude of which Voltaire was a supreme philosophical weathervane coincided with a rapid reshaping of music after the deaths of Bach and Handel.
reshaping.example2: For Darwin, Lyell’s central idea—of the slow heave of natural forces shaping and reshaping the earth, sculpting nature—would prove to be a potent intellectual spur.
reshaping.example3: In the shower, I note that I’m reshaping.

refactor.definition: The process by which source code is refactored.

perfectionism.definition: An unwillingness to settle for anything less than perfection.
perfectionism.example1: Most other kids were either jealous of her or found her perfectionism annoying.
perfectionism.example2: His perfectionism seemed absolute, even when they took walks to other villages and he insisted on quizzing her about the Latin names of plants they saw.
perfectionism.example3: In the theater, passion and perfectionism and insistence on aesthetic standards are prized qualities, not unruly and unwelcome traits.

maintainer.definition: Someone who keeps or upholds something; a steward.
maintainer.example1: The trail maintainers in Maine have a certain hale devotion to seeking out the rockiest climbs and most forbidding slopes, and of these Maine has a breathtaking plenitude.
maintainer.example2: Each village in Bali has at least three temples, one for each of the Hindu trimurti, or trinity: Brahma the creator, Vishnu the maintainer and Shiva the destroyer.

provenance.example1: Researchers must reckon their ages by ascertaining the age of the ground they are found in, which in turn requires meticulously documenting their provenance.
provenance.example2: Beginning in the Administration Building, with a single wind tunnel, the lab grew until space limits pushed it to expand to the west onto several large properties tracing their provenance to colonial-era plantations.
provenance.example3: I think of the letter I found on Balekin’s desk, the one to Nicasia’s mother: I know the provenance of the blusher mushroom that you ask after.

spunk.example1: You want one with spunk but at the same time ain’t too stubborn.
spunk.example2: Someone with spunk, someone who lets nothing stop her from reaching her dreams.
spunk.example3: “And look at you now, going to your fancy colegio, living in your fancy hotel. Nothing stops you! You have as much spunk as ever, little sister.”

kip.definition: The untanned hide of a young or small beast, such as a calf, lamb, or young goat.
kip.example1: I mounted the bar with a kip and swung myself up to the handstand.
kip.example2: “He wants a kip, and his bar’s turned into a railway station.”
kip.example3: You see an animal on it’s side and you’re like: “Please be a narcoleptic, please don’t be dying, please be having a kip.”

affront.definition: An open or intentional offense, slight, or insult.
affront.example1: Wick got his pass back, but he could not easily overlook the affront to his intellectual independence.
affront.example2: It’s as if she assumes everything will go right, and when it doesn’t—which, of course, is pretty often—she is surprised and affronted.
affront.example3: Chattel slavery was an affront to God, and slavers an aspect of Satan.

landfall.definition: Arrival at the shore by ship.
landfall.example1: Having crossed the Weddell Sea, Shackleton would make landfall at the best opportunity, and then set out across the continent.
landfall.example2: On the other hand, trying to sail around to the other side put them at risk of being swept past the island and into the Atlantic with no landfall before Africa.
landfall.example3: When on the East the sheer bright star arose that tells of coming Dawn, the ship made landfall and came up islandward in the dim of night.

tentatively.definition: Of, or having to do with being tentative.
tentatively.example1: You patted your grave, tentatively, like you were considering his words.
tentatively.example2: I pushed a button on the dashboard, which had a big D for Drive on it, and tentatively pressed down on the gas and we inched forward.
tentatively.example3: “According to one of our insiders, your execution is tentatively scheduled for two weeks from today,” he says.

fiver.definition: A banknote with a value of five units of currency.
fiver.example1: Back went the fiver and out came a tenner!
fiver.example2: From the corners of my eyes I saw Mpandhlani give the piece of fiver to a five-year-old boy.
fiver.example3: The notes weren't fivers, nor tenners; they were all twenty-pound notes.

bonehead.definition: Someone who is stubborn, thick-skulled, or stupid.
bonehead.example1: “Yeah, and there might be enough to go around for once, without this bonehead hogging the butter and syrup.”
bonehead.example2: But even though the labels have changed over the years—from “bonehead,” to “remedial,” to “basic”— the effects are still the same.

yielding.definition: To pay, give in payment; repay, recompense; reward; requite.

yielding.example2: All of the hope that had sprung there, growing and spreading and yielding like a stream, had dried up in an instant.

underfoot.definition: A storage compartment that sits below the deck of a boat.

colitis.example1: At John’s insistence, Ernest was transferred across the bay to Palo Alto Hospital, the better to consult with its Dr. Albert Snell, one of the nations preeminent specialists in colitis.

wormwood.definition: An intensely bitter herb (Artemisia absinthium and similar plants in genus Artemisia) used in medicine, in the production of absinthe and vermouth, and as a tonic.
